Below is a concise and efficient implementation of the **bubble sort** algorithm in Java:

```java
public class BubbleSort {

    public static void bubbleSort(int[] arr) {
        int n = arr.length;
        boolean swapped;

        do {
            swapped = false;
            for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
                if (arr[i - 1] > arr[i]) {
                    // Swap adjacent elements if they are out of order
                    int temp = arr[i - 1];
                    arr[i - 1] = arr[i];
                    arr[i] = temp;
                    swapped = true;
                }
            }
            // Optimization: if no swaps were made, array is already sorted
            if (!swapped) break;
            n--; // Reduce the number of comparisons as largest element moves to end
        } while (swapped);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
        System.out.println("Before sorting: " + java.util.Arrays.toString(arr));
        bubbleSort(arr);
        System.out.println("After sorting: " + java.util.Arrays.toString(arr));
    }
}
```

### How it works:
- **Outer loop**: Iterates through the entire list, reducing the search area with each pass since the largest elements "bubble up."
- **Inner loop**: Compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are out of order.
- **Optimization**: As soon as no swaps occur, the array is considered sorted, and the loop terminates early.

### Output:
```
Before sorting: [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]
After sorting: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]
``` 

This implementation adheres to the expected behavior and constraints of bubble sort.

Below is a correct and efficient implementation of **insertion sort** in Java:

```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class InsertionSort {

    public static void insertionSort(int[] arr) {
        for (int i = 1; i < arr.length; i++) {
            int key = arr[i]; // Current element to insert
            int j = i - 1;

            // Shift elements greater than key to one position ahead
            while (j >= 0 && arr[j] > key) {
                arr[j + 1] = arr[j];
                j--;
            }
            arr[j + 1] = key; // Place current element at its correct location
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
        System.out.println("Before sorting: " + Arrays.toString(arr));
        insertionSort(arr);
        System.out.println("After sorting: " + Arrays.toString(arr));
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
- **Insertion Sort** is an efficient comparison-based sorting technique that builds the final sorted array one item at a time.
- **Time Complexity**: Worst case O(n²), average case O(n²), best case O(n) when the array is already sorted.
- **Space Complexity**: O(1) auxiliary space.

### Sample output:
```
Before sorting: [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]
After sorting: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]
```

